ce:section.ce:para:
The formation of photoluminescent nano CDs (PNCDs) was evident by their distinct colour change from light brown in visible light to bright blue fluorescence under ultraviolet light, as shown in Fig. 1
                        A. The presence of two distinct functional groups in PNCD was evident from the electronic spectra corresponding to CC (π → π*) and CO (n → π*) at 274 and 320 nm, respectively [22]. The long-term stability of the fluorescence was studied by prolonged exposure to UV–visible radiation for 5 to 180 min, and no discernible change in absorbance was observed in the case of a two-month-old PNCD [7]. The excitation-dependent fluorescence spectra of aqueous PNCDs are depicted in Fig. 1B. The photoluminescence (PL) spectra were continuously captured at intervals of 20 nm between excitation wavelengths of 300 and 500 nm. It was observed that (Fig. 1C) excitation at a wavelength of 380 nm generated the most intense emission peak at 460 nm. The emission lines from 450 to 550 nm were red-shifted with an intensity reduction at excitation wavelengths between 400 and 500 nm. The fluctuations in the intensity of the emission spectra reflected the surface morphology of PNCD particles. The intricate chemical groups and erratic size of PNCDs gave rise to this structural feature, which influenced the band structure [23]. Furthermore, the PNCDs had an excellent fluorescence quantum yield of 10.53 %, compared to CDs derived from other green sources [24]. Lifetime measurement was also conducted to confirm the durability of PNCDs. The decay curve, with a lifetime of 3.67±0.01 ns (χ2 = 0.99), is depicted in Fig. 1D [25]. The average size of PNCDs (Fig. 1E) was found to be 38 nm, somewhat larger than the size (5.85 nm) measured using TEM. This difference in size may be attributed to the fact that the particle's hydrodynamic diameter in a solvent is greater than its size measured in a vacuum [26]. The broad, noisy diffraction hump pattern obtained at 2θ=23.29° (Fig. 1F) revealed the amorphous nature of the highly disordered C atoms in the as-synthesized PNCDs. This spectrum demonstrated the (002) Bragg peak from the graphitic core (lattice plane) [27]. The direct structural imaging of the PNCD at the nano scale was done with HR-TEM, showing the well-scattered black sphere-like PNCDs (Fig. 2
                        ). According to the histogram, the Gaussian fitting curve revealed that the average size of these PNCDs was about 5 .85nm. The interlayer spacing of 0.19 nm in the 002 graphitic in-plane lattice of PNCDs was observed in the image, suggesting that graphene-like carbon cores were formed after hydrothermal treatment [28,29]. The amorphous structure was shown by the large circles in the chosen area of the electron diffraction (SAED) micrograph pattern [26,28]. The existence of bands at 3381, 2854, 2924, 1638, 1405, 1051, and 641cm-1 in the vibrational spectrum (figure S1A) was characteristic of OH and NH stretching, CH symmetric and asymmetric stretching, C = O, C = N, CO and =CH bond vibrations, respectively [30]. Selection of PNCDs as filler particles in polymer coatings was primarily motivated by the abundance of these electron-rich moieties. Two broad Raman peaks at 1354 and 1527cm-1 in figure S1B indicated the D and G bands, reflecting sp3 disordered carbon atoms and the sp2 hybridized graphitic core area, respectively. Due to the doping of nitrogen in the PNCD carbon framework, the ID band exhibited somewhat greater intensity than the IG band, indicating defects in the sp2 carbon lattice [31]. Furthermore, the extensively graphitized carbon atoms were indicated by the ID/IG ratio of 0.88 [28].

The FTIR-ATR spectra (Fig. 6
                           ) of ESD, compared to the plain epoxy coating, show a broad and sharp peak around 3000–3500cm-1, which indicates the OH and NH bond vibrations from the nanofiller component. The presence of a peak at 1640 cm-1 is assigned to the C = O/ Si-OH functional group. The successful dispersion of the filler particles was confirmed by the symmetric stretching vibration of the filled silica nanoparticle at a wavelength of 1100cm-1. Then, O-Si-O and Si-O-Si bond vibrations were also clearly visible in the spectra of the composite film. Therefore, the FTIR-ATR spectra figure out that the SPNCD's were successfully blended in to the epoxy matrix, exposing the active PNCD functional moieties for corrosion prevention. The DRS UV-visible spectrum (Fig. 7
                           ) shows only two prominent peaks. Both peaks are characteristic of PNCD particles. The XPS technique was used to explain the chemical composition of the ESD. The XPS survey spectra of both PNCD and ESD are shown in Fig. 8
                           . The survey spectrum of the PNCD particles displays three unique peaks associated with C1 s, N1 s, and O1 s at 284.9, 399.8, and 530.7 eV The analysis revealed the presence of 76.68 % C, 7.61 % N, and 15.71 % O in the PNCD. Similarly, the ESD also showed three signals at 289.5, 404.6, and 536.62 eV Moreover, an additional signal at 108.3 eV corresponds to Si 2p from the silica nanoparticles. Since the C atoms in ESD were exposed to five different chemical environments, the high-resolution C1 s spectrum displayed five distinct peaks at 284.06, 284.8, 285.6, 285.7, and 288.28 eV, corresponding to the CC, C-Si/ C = C, C = N, Si-O-C/CO-C/CN, and C = O species, respectively. The high-resolution N1 s spectrum exhibits one peak at 399.5 eV, corresponding to the CN bond from the PNCD, and another peak at 400.9 eV, which corresponds to the NH bond. The O1 s spectrum was resolved into four distinct signals. The signal at 530.6 eV is attributed to the C = O group. Moreover, the peaks at 531.4, 532.2, and 532.8 eV peaks correspond to Si-O-C, CO-C or COH, and Si-OH groups, respectively. Similarly, high-resolution Si2p peaks at 103.9 and 104.8 eV correspond to Si-OH and Si-O-Si, respectively, indicating that the silica nanoparticles interact neither with the epoxy matrix nor with the CD's. Silica nanoparticles act as an effective filler and adsorbent for PNCD particles. Moreover, the XPS study confirms that the surface of ESD contains the active functional groups of PNCD. The effect of PNCD particles on the anticorrosion properties was studied using SEM analysis. The epoxy-coated metal surface (Fig. 9
                           A) exhibits numerous pores, and these pore sites allow corrosive ions to penetrate through the sample, scrunch the substrate more easily. Fig. 9B displays the crack initiation surface of the epoxy after 24 h of immersion in electrolytic media. When 0.4 % SPNCD is incorporated into the epoxy matrix, most of the pores are covered, resulting in a smoother surface on the MS (Fig. 9C). The nanoscale scanning of the probe on the metal surface provided a clear image of uniformly distributed spherical filler particles on the epoxy base. The reduced level of pores would be beneficial in inhibiting the attack of corrosive ions and reducing the extent of metal degradation. Fig. 9D shows a fracture-free surface of the ESD coated sample after 24-hour corrosion study, compared to the epoxy coated MS (Fig. 9B).
